Restoring the very American ideal that labor rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a law to protect trade union organization as a civil right.
“Depending on how unions work, middle-class jobs work,” said Ellison, a Minnesota Democratic senator who co-chairs the Congressional Committee.
That is why I am so proud to present a law strengthening the position of employees, along with John Lewis's model of occasional rights.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination in trade union organisation as other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-competitive forces
Adjusting the Employment Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination to join unions, to sue in a civil court - and to prosecute compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other lawmakers are proposing in the law is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states - Americans once supported countries around the world to adopt, extend and respect labor rights.
There were times, and millions of Americans still remember them, when the country in one breath promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers supported the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toya’s military autocracy would be replaced by democracy.
They believed that employees and their unions were playing a role in shaping the new Japan, including language and openly acknowledging that “the right of employees to assemble, collectively negotiate and act is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans, realizing that workers would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, included a clause that openly stated: “The right to create associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or profession.
Arrangements that will restrict or seek to damage this right will be revoked. Measures leading to the fulfillment of such purpose are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide treaty in 1948, the petitioners and Roosevelt included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to form and join unions in the protection of his interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to form labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as equal partners - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and assert themselves in a free and open society.
As Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today everyone knows that the trade unions did not reduce the strength of the nation, but expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an unforeseen level.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights so as to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that raised America and made it a true promise of democracy.
Judge Temporarily Blocks Law That Could Shut Down All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that lawyers said would likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
The decree, signed by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June and due to enter into force on September 1, would require abortion doctors to have the right to receive a patient in a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge's ruling means that doctors can temporarily continue to perform legal abortions and in the meantime must obtain this permission.
“The proposed party will be able to legally conduct its activities and, in the meantime, obtain a permit,” Federal Judge John deGravelles said in a ruling.
The hearing will be scheduled within one month so that the judge can issue a more permanent resolution on the law.
Activists for abortion rights welcomed the resolution, which is the latest in a series of similar measures, and said it would give doctors more time to get permission.
“Today’s decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from the insidious law that is supposed to deprive them of their health and their rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and chief executive of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit on behalf of three out of five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applied to doctors from two clinics who were not among the plaintiffs and also applied for this authorisation.
Louisiana is among the 11 states that have passed similar laws, with the Alabama and Mississippi courts declaring such measures unconstitutional.
Key parts of the Texas law that would shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for women’s rights to abortion, together with the American Association of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, argue that the need to have this permission imposes medical requirements that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argued that the measures were intended to protect women’s health, and some also welcomed the fact that clinics would be closed because of the measures.
According to the Center for Reproductive Rights, only one doctor in Louisiana is allowed to perform abortions.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure out of fear for his safety, the group said.
Louisiana authorities said in response that they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while waiting for the application to be granted rights.
