Why can the universe have multiple dimensions and we can’t see them?
Physicists usually don’t write bestsellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University managed to hit the black in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for laymen to penetrate the denseness of problems that many theoretical physicists are dealing with today – an attempt to unify two well-functioning but mutually incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that the search for a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the fundamental problem between two key theories (in fact, at this moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) in such an imaginative way that it is worth retelling even to laymen.
In addition, Greene dealt with the complex material so freshly and engagingly that it is impossible to blame him for how much interesting he did not include in his book.
In addition, he corrected his "mistake" for the most part in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and Hidden Reality.
Apparently, even the author would not object to his book becoming obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything that an informed layman with an ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will still be a little more lively in this area (for example, because the LHC accelerator will finally go on "full gas"), so it is a good time to enter Green's non-violently open doors to the world of modern physics.
How big can our universe be?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound silly, fantastic, strange, or mystical.
However, it is concrete and completely acceptable.
In order to understand this, let us turn our eyes for a moment from the universe as a whole to something more ground-based, specifically to a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine stretching a 100-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the whole scenery from a half-kilometer distance (as in the picture and on the following page).
From such a distance, you can easily notice a long horizontally stretched hose, but if you do not suffer from clairvoyance, you can hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on the hose has only one dimension in which it can walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at the time, you answer with only one information: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from a half-kilometre distance, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose is thick.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see the second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In this enlarged view, it is obvious that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/against the direction of movement of the clock hands", i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant you need to enter two numbers: how far from the end of the hose and where the circle wraps the hose.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note that experts note that this chapter focuses purely on the fault theory of strings.
Non-disruptive aspects are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.).
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circumference, indicated by a circular arrow, is short and bent.
However, there is a clear difference between the two dimensions.
The size along the hose is long and easily visible.
The size of the wrapping circumference of the hose is short, "twisted" and less noticeable.
To realize the existence of the circular dimension, we had to study the hose with a significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important feature of spatial dimensions.
The fact that they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, large, and therefore directly visible, or, on the contrary, small, bent, and much worse observable.
Of course, in this case, we didn't just skip ahead to reveal the "twisted" dimension wrapping the thickness of the hose.
I just needed a telescope to help me.
But if the hose had been thinner - like a hair or a capillary - we would have discovered the coiled dimension only with great effort.
In 1919, Kaluza sent Einstein an article in which he expressed the astonishing idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions known to all of us.
Kaluza justified his radical claim by providing an elegant and convincing framework in which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises as to how this Kaluza observation goes along with the obvious fact that we see precisely the three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly expressed and clarified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the assertion that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and coiled dimensions.
This means that, like the dimension in the direction of the length of the hose, our universe has large, vast and easily visible three dimensions, the existence of which we are aware of at every moment.
But analogously with the circular circumference of the garden hose, the universe can have additional dimensions, tightly folded into space so small that they have so far remained hidden even from our most perfect experimental apparatus.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluzov's remarkable design, let's stay with the hose for a while.
Imagine that on the circumference of the hose draw in black a fairly dense series of circles.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With the telescope, thanks to the drawing, we will now reveal the folded dimension even more easily, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but apart from one small circular dimension it has three large spatial dimensions, that is, four spatial dimensions.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imagination a little, let us note the illustration in Fig. 3; it shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of space in the same way as we enlarge the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of space from the previous level.
Our universe can have additional dimensions (we see them on the fourth level of magnification) if they are folded into a sufficiently small space; this explains that we have not yet directly observed them.
A square grid represents the commonly known "big" dimensions, while a circle represents a new, tiny and coiled dimension.
Just like the thread loops in the densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of the usual dimensions - just for the sake of clarity, we have drawn them only in the intersections in the square mesh.
The background of Figure 4 depicts the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - in such common scales as meters,represented by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each picture below, we will focus on a small area of the previous image; we will zoom in to make it visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see at the first few levels of magnification.
However, as we advance on our way to the microscopic properties of the geometry of space further - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we see suddenly a new, circle-shaped, twisted dimension, similar to strings of thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every point in the direction of large dimensions, just as the hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have mapped the circular dimension only in some regularly distributed points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluzov and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of space geometry.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also notice important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-flung spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has only one large dimension.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just about some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the extra rounded dimension is extremely miniature, it is much more difficult to recognize it - like the circular circumference of the hose - than to observe the obvious, large and vast dimensions.
If the size of the extra dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it even beyond the strength of our most modern instruments for magnification.
Most importantly, however, the extra dimension is not just a rounded bump inside the normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration misleadingly suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of the three common vast dimensions.
It is a dimension on the other three dimensions independent as well as the top-down, left-right and front-back dimensions independent (and perpendicular) of each other.
A sufficiently small ant could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the usual three still a position in the circular dimension; if we count the time, then the data five, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
