To our surprise, therefore, we find that, although we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluzov and Klein’s reasoning shows that this does not exclude the existence of additional folded dimensions, if they are small enough.
The universe can have more dimensions than we can see with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
The state-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize the structures of a large billionth of a billionth of a meter.
Smaller folded dimensions can hardly be observed.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluz's original idea with several ideas from the newly emerging quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the extra circular dimension could be about the size of one Planck length, a size far beyond the distinctiveness of today's instruments.
Since then, physicists have called the possibility of additional small spatial dimensions Kaluzov-Klein theory.
