Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed.
A British woman describes how, after a bad diagnosis, she thought she would die for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking she only had a few years to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth Syndrome (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said that poor diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
It is estimated that approximately 23,000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which can manifest symptoms in the area of motor skills such as muscle weakness, clumsy walking and twisted toes.
The affected may also experience numbness or pain, this condition is incurable and progressive, which means that over time the symptoms worsen.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich's Ataxia (FA), a disease that has a very poor prognosis.
She believed that by the time she celebrated her eighteenth birthday, she would be strapped to a wheelchair, and dead before she was thirty.
A mother of two, now 51, says: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same things as the others.
Every day I fell and everything took longer.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboards with other kids, and I was bullied in school because of the way I walked and ran.”
When Rodgers was thirteen and had several surgeries to relax her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of her doctor’s departure from the room and looked into her records to learn that she was suffering from FA.
“I felt guilty because I was spying, so I didn’t tell anyone, but when I came home, I looked up information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Association,” she says.
When they answered me, I was in shock, I panicked completely.
I thought that by the time I was eighteen, I would end up in a wheelchair, and by the time I was twenty-five, I would be dead, and in the meantime I would gradually lose all my powers.
I was on my own and I was planning a funeral.”
When she was seventeen, she realized that her walking ability had not deteriorated as much as she had expected, and she asked her surgeon about it.
He just stood up, hugged her, and said, "Honey, I don't think you have the disease, or you'd be in a wheelchair by now.
I think it will be something much less life-threatening.”
After undergoing several genetic tests, it was found that he had CMT.
"When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a lucky child," she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched a month of awareness of CMT to raise awareness of the disease.
Entrepreneurs in the Washington area: with the turnover of the economy, taxes are rising
A growing economy means more customers, more sales and more jobs.
And higher taxes too.
According to a new survey published last week, the state and local taxation of businesses in the country with the acceleration of the recovery of the economy grew slightly last year, and companies in Washington were no exception.
Businesses in Maryland and Virginia collectively contributed $27.6 billion to state and local treasuries in fiscal year 2013, up 3.8% from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
Tax burdens – both state and local – rose 4.3% to $671 billion last year, up from 3.9% last year, and were the third consecutive growth year after 2009 and 2010, when taxes were falling.
According to a study carried out by Ernst & Young and the Center on State Taxation, state taxes increased faster, by 4.3% than local taxes, by 3.9%.
More than half of the county's tax revenues, 56%, are from trade tax, and 36% of Maryland's revenues are from companies.
Virginia, with 28%, has proportionally the lowest tax revenue from business.
The majority of growth in tax revenues comes from an increase in the value of real estate belonging to companies, which increased property taxes this year after three consecutive years with growth of -1% by 3.7%.
Although most of the profits come from big states like California, New York and Texas, it seems the same situation is in Washington.
Companies in D.C., Maryland and Virginia paid more than $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up 4.2% year-on-year from $9.6 billion in 2012.
However, the apparent increase in property value does not so much elevate state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate tax accounts for less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For businesses in Virginia and D.C., property tax accounts for nearly half of state and local taxes.
“Maryland owns a lot of real estate companies, especially the tax base around D.C., the government or a non-profit organization that doesn’t pay taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
So Maryland is forced to rely much more on, for example, income taxes to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent increase in business tax revenues cannot be attributed only to the recovering real estate market.
According to the data, business income also appears to be increasing.
Companies in the region have posted a $2.3 billion corporate income tax, up from $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland raised $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the most in the region.
Although they are moving in the same direction, the local tax burden on entrepreneurs is not growing as fast in these three places.
The growth rate in D.C. was at the national average, at 4.3%, while Maryland's growth was significantly higher, at 4.9%.
In Virginia alone, the tax increase was below average, to 4.1%.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax rate of any of the three districts (all of which have the same tax rate) at 6%.
The corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25%, while the average D.C. remains relatively high, at 9.975%.
A similar study conducted this year by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce showed that Virginia has lower state and local taxes and a generally more favorable tax climate than Maryland.
The D.C. study was not evaluated.
Despite this advantage, Virginia faces the pressure of competition from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a law cutting the corporate tax from 6.9% to 6%, as did Virginia, and the tax will be reduced to 5% next year.
If the state continues to meet income targets in the coming year, the statutory income tax rate could be reduced to 3% in 2017.
According to a recent study, small businesses in Washington are doing better and therefore pay higher state and local taxes.
Trade tax paid by small businesses as a personal income tax — a structure that compensates for cost increases by increasing the prices at which most businesses are organized — rose 20% last year to $2.4 billion in D.C., Maryland, and Virginia, much faster than other taxes.
Researchers say the trend and nationwide increase in trade tax is likely to continue next year, with total tax revenues from sales to state and local governments rising to 6.2% in the same period last year in the first three quarters of 2014.
But Washington may be lagging behind because cutting government spending is taxing the labor market.
